'''Rick Kirkman''' (born 1953) is a [[cartoonist]] and co-creator of the [[comic strip]] ''[[Baby Blues]]''. He received the [[National Cartoonist Society]] Newspaper Comic Strip Award in [[1995 in comics|1995]], and the [[Reuben Award]] in 2012 for his work on the strip. He also served as co-executive producer of the WB Network TV series of Baby Blues.

Prior to the creation of Baby Blues, Rick Kirkman worked as a humorous [[illustrator]] and gag cartoonist. His gag cartoons appeared in magazines including [[Saturday Evening Post]], [[Saturday Review (US magazine)|Saturday Review]] and [[Good Housekeeping]]. He created humorous illustrations for advertising clients including [[America West Airlines]], [[BIC Corporation]], [[Campbell Soup Company|Campbells]], [[Ramada Inn]] and [[Best Western]]; and accompanying articles in [[Parents Magazine]], [[Money (magazine)|Money]], [[Children's Television Workshop]] and [[Redbook]].

He collaborated with longtime friend, [[Jerry Scott]], to create the comic strip Baby Blues, which was launched in [[1990 in comics|1990]] by [[Creators Syndicate]].

